  "text": "An exciting alternative to maize for agricultural biogas plants may provide wetland biomass, which use for energy generation was proved to be more environmental and social friendly compared to energy crops. A substantial amount of Phragmites australis, Phalaris arundinacea, and Carex sp. is harvested annually in Poland as a part of wetland conservation programs [CITATION_1] . Studies so far, which are few, indicate that wetland biomass could be a good co-substrate in agricultural biogas plants, with methane productivity that is comparable to swine manure [CITATION_2] . There is also little research on the quality of digestate obtained in anaerobic digestion from wetland plants.",
